{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:09:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:09:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0,0.9,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24517"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA phaeochromocytoma is an uncommon neuroendocrine tumour that forms in the adrenal gland. It is associated with a particular group of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the classic triad of symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal pain, fever, weight loss","Chest pain, dyspnoea, syncope","Fatigue, dizziness, blurred vision","Headaches, sweating, palpitations","Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classic triad of symptoms associated with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ephaeochromocytoma\u003C/strong\u003E includes headaches, sweating and palpitations. These symptoms are due to the excessive secretion of catecholamines by the tumour, leading to episodic hypertension and adrenergic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal pain, fever, weight loss\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically associated with phaeochromocytoma. These symptoms might suggest other conditions such as infections or malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest pain, dyspnoea, syncope\u003C/strong\u003E could be related to cardiac issues or other causes of acute distress but are not the classic presentation of phaeochromocytoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENausea, vomiting, diarrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E are gastrointestinal symptoms that are not part of the classic triad for phaeochromocytoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatigue, dizziness, blurred vision\u003C/strong\u003E are non-specific symptoms that can be seen in a variety of conditions but do not form the classic triad for phaeochromocytoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phaeochromocytoma is a rare tumour of the adrenal gland that secretes catecholamines, leading to episodic symptoms.","The classic triad of symptoms for phaeochromocytoma includes headaches, sweating, and palpitations.","Diagnosis is often confirmed through biochemical testing and imaging studies."],"references":["Cerqueira A, Seco T, Costa A, Tavares M, Cotter J. Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma: A Review of Diagnosis, Management and Treatment of Rare Causes of Hypertension. Cureus. 2020 May 5;12(5):e7969. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7969. PMID: 32523826; PMCID: PMC7273359.","Patel T, Singleton LA, Mejia M, Senior A, Millis RM. Pheochromocytoma: A Troublesome Tumor. Cureus. 2023 Sep 18;15(9):e45490. doi: 10.7759/cureus.45490. PMID: 37727845; PMCID: PMC10506759.","Manger WM, Gifford RW. Pheochromocytoma. J Clin Hypertens (Greenwich). 2002 Jan-Feb;4(1):62-72. doi: 10.1111/j.1524-6175.2002.01452.x. PMID: 11821644; PMCID: PMC8099329.","Farrugia FA, Charalampopoulos A. Pheochromocytoma. Endocr Regul. 2019 Jul 1;53(3):191-212. doi: 10.2478/enr-2019-0020. PMID: 31517632."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57841"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T09:50:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T09:50:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10502"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"em